      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Aaron Crofut" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Aaron Crofut" href="/user/show/4096056-aaron-crofut">Aaron Crofut</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Mass Market Paperback 9780671411312" href="/book/show/10208121-terrible-swift-sword">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4096056-aaron-crofut?shelf=history">history</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4096056-aaron-crofut?shelf=civil-war">civil-war</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2752473226" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17189966840988332119">Catton&apos;s work is a gripping account of the Civil War transforming itself from the cause of preserving the Union to one of redefining what that Union stood for. Lincoln subtly navigates the ship of state, an unwieldy ship if there ever was one, through the rocky shoals of civil war. Radical Republicans and abolitionists, the border state slave owners and moderate Democrats effectively controlling the premier army of the North, the active foil of the Confederacy with Britain always playing an unce</span>
  <span id="freeText17189966840988332119" style="display:none">Catton's work is a gripping account of the Civil War transforming itself from the cause of preserving the Union to one of redefining what that Union stood for. Lincoln subtly navigates the ship of state, an unwieldy ship if there ever was one, through the rocky shoals of civil war. Radical Republicans and abolitionists, the border state slave owners and moderate Democrats effectively controlling the premier army of the North, the active foil of the Confederacy with Britain always playing an uncertain role off in the distance...and of course chance ever determining the course of nations all weigh on the President as he both tries to win the war and define why that war must be fought and won in the first place. <br /><br />It doesn't surprise me that a generation of Civil War buffs were raised after the likes of Shelby Foote and Bruce Catton started writing expansive and engaging accounts of the conflict. This is history as it is supposed to be. Highly recommended! </span>
  <a data-text-id="17189966840988332119" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


